const GRC2 = `<svg viewBox="0 0 460 300" width="100%" style="max-width:480px;height:auto" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="DM Sans, system-ui, sans-serif"><rect x="0" y="0" width="460" height="300" fill="#f8fafc"/><line x1="30" y1="272" x2="440" y2="272" stroke="#0a1628" stroke-width="2"/><ellipse cx="101" cy="96" rx="20" ry="13" fill="#9ca3af"/><ellipse cx="125" cy="76" rx="27" ry="16" fill="#9ca3af"/><ellipse cx="162" cy="68" rx="32" ry="19" fill="#9ca3af"/><text x="150" y="72" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" font-weight="700" fill="#1f2937">EMISSIONS</text><rect x="60" y="150" width="160" height="122" fill="#cbd5e1" stroke="#0a1628" stroke-width="2"/><rect x="92" y="108" width="22" height="44" fill="#94a3b8" stroke="#0a1628" stroke-width="2"/><rect x="152" y="120" width="22" height="32" fill="#94a3b8" stroke="#0a1628" stroke-width="2"/><text x="140" y="220" text-anchor="middle" font-size="13" font-weight="700" fill="#0a1628">OUR FACTORY</text><rect x="300" y="250" width="26" height="20" fill="#a16207"/><line x1="313" y1="250" x2="313" y2="230" stroke="#15803d" stroke-width="3"/><circle cx="313" cy="226" r="9" fill="#22c55e"/><text x="313" y="289" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#0a1628">OFFSET</text><rect x="298" y="176" width="154" height="26" rx="7" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#0a1628"/><text x="375" y="193" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="#0a1628">We are going green!</text><circle cx="392" cy="214" r="10" fill="#0ea5e9"/><line x1="392" y1="224" x2="392" y2="250" stroke="#0a1628" stroke-width="3"/><line x1="392" y1="231" x2="350" y2="234" stroke="#0a1628" stroke-width="3"/><line x1="392" y1="231" x2="408" y2="244" stroke="#0a1628" stroke-width="3"/><line x1="392" y1="250" x2="384" y2="272" stroke="#0a1628" stroke-width="3"/><line x1="392" y1="250" x2="400" y2="272" stroke="#0a1628" stroke-width="3"/></svg>`;

const HSA = "A photograph, unlike a memory, does not fade; and it is precisely this permanence that makes it treacherous. The remembered face softens and recomposes itself with each recollection, absorbing the moods of the rememberer until it becomes less a record than a companion. The photographed face, by contrast, is fixed at an instant the sitter did not choose and cannot revise. We imagine that the photograph preserves the past, but what it preserves is only a surface, severed from the duration that gave it meaning. To look at an old photograph is therefore to be confronted not with the past itself but with its irrecoverable exterior, and the melancholy peculiar to such images arises from this: they show us everything except the one thing we want, which is the continuance of the moment beyond its own border.";
const HSB = "It is fashionable to insist that, in a democracy, every opinion deserves equal weight. The principle is generous, but it conflates two things that ought to be kept apart: the equal right to hold an opinion and the unequal reliability of opinions once held. A citizen's right to a view on the safety of a bridge is indeed equal to an engineer's; the worth of their views, as guides to whether the bridge will stand, is not. To treat the two as identical is not to honour democracy but to abolish the very notion of expertise, and with it the possibility that some questions have answers at all. The democratic instinct is sound where it concerns ends, the values a society chooses to pursue; it becomes incoherent only when extended to means, the technical questions of how those ends might be reached.";
const HSC = "We speak of progress as though it were a single road leading in one direction, so that to move along it is necessarily to improve. But the metaphor flatters us. A society may grow richer while growing more anxious, more connected while growing lonelier, more capable while growing less wise. Each of these advances is real; none is illusory; yet their sum does not obviously point one way. The error lies in supposing that because we can measure some things, those are the things that matter, and that what eludes measurement may be safely ignored. A civilisation that mistakes its instruments for its purposes will keep its accounts impeccably and lose, without noticing, the very goods the accounts were meant to serve.";
const HSD = "What the Map Omits\n\nThe cartographer, who loved his country, drew\neach river truer than the rivers were,\nand where a marsh had drowned a hopeful road\nhe inked a firm intention through the blur.\n\nHis maps were beautiful. Men set their course\nby confident green meadows that, in fact,\nwere bog; and cursed, waist-deep, the careful hand\nthat drew the world it wished, and called it fact.\n\nYet who would keep the other kind of map,\nall honest swamp, no promise in the lines?\nWe ask of those who chart us, not the truth,\nbut somewhere firm to stand among the signs.";

const VH1 = `To say that we live in the present is to say less than we suppose, for the present we are given is never the bare point at which a note sounds, but a thickened now in which that note still trails the one before it and already leans toward the one to come. Strip away that fringe and the melody collapses into a succession of unrelated instants, none of which could be heard as music. What we call hearing a phrase, then, is not the adding of remembered notes to a present one, as though memory reached back to fetch them; it is rather that the just-elapsed is still given, sinking but not yet absent, while the not-yet is sketched in advance by the very shape of what we have heard. Consciousness does not occupy time as a body occupies a chair. It holds open a span within which alone there can be any object at all.`;
const VH2 = `Suppose that what makes you the same person tomorrow as today is not the persistence of a single substance, a soul or an unbroken body, but the holding-together of overlapping psychological connections: memories that reach back, intentions that reach forward, a character that bends only slowly. If so, identity admits of degree, and the question of whether some far future person will be you may have no sharp answer where the connections thin. The discomfort this produces is instructive. We had assumed that personal identity was the deep fact on which the rationality of self-concern rested, that I save for my old age because that pensioner will be me. But if identity is only the name we give to a sufficiently dense web of relations, then perhaps it was never identity that mattered, and what we owe our future selves we may owe, in lesser measure, to others to whom we are bound as well.`;
const VH3 = `Imagine a forgery so perfect that no instrument and no eye could tell it from the original: every crack in the varnish, every hesitation of the brush, reproduced. The puzzle is not whether we could detect the fraud but whether, undetected, it would be as good. Those who say it must be, since nothing perceptible distinguishes the two, assume that the value of a painting is exhausted by how it looks. Yet our experience of a work is not the experience of a coloured surface alone but of an achievement, a thing meant and made at a particular moment by a particular hand reaching beyond what had been done before. The forgery, however dazzling its surface, is parasitic: it reaches only toward another painting. To call the two equal is not to praise the copy but to forget what we were valuing in the original.`;
const HD1 = `I have always been, my sister says, the reasonable one, and I see no cause to dispute a description so obviously just. When our mother's house was to be divided, it was I who proposed that we each take what we valued and leave the rest to sober arithmetic; and if the few good pieces happened to be the ones I valued, that is hardly an argument against a fair principle. Clara wept, of course. Clara has always wept easily, which is its own kind of advantage, though I would never say so to her face. I contented myself with observing that sentiment is a poor basis for the settlement of an estate, and that one of us, at least, had kept her head.`;
const HD2 = `We kept the clock our grandfather had wound
long after it had any right to keep
the time; its hands, arrested, had not found
the hour in years, and yet we let it sleep

upon the shelf, as though to take it down
would be to grant the morning it had stopped.
A broken clock is honest twice; we frown
at honesty so seldom, and so opt

to keep the lie that something has not moved.
The stopped hands point, and what they point me to
is not a time at all, but time arranged
to spare us from the little that is true.`;
const HD3 = `The shelves groan with the memoirs of the successful, each pressing upon us the habits to which the author attributes a fortune: rise early, take the risk, trust the gut. The advice is delivered with the confidence of one who tried it and won. What the genre cannot show us, because they did not write books, are the many who rose just as early, took the same risk, trusted the same gut, and failed. Without them the sample is not merely incomplete; it is chosen by the very outcome it claims to explain. A habit shared by winners and losers alike explains nothing about winning, however vividly the winner remembers it.`;
const HD4 = `The new clerk had been blamed for the missing money, and I knew, as surely as I knew my own name, that he had not taken it, for I had seen the under-manager at the drawer myself. But the under-manager was a friend to my advancement, and the clerk was no one, and the words I might have said grew heavier the longer I held them, until they were too heavy to lift at all. I told myself I would speak if it came to dismissal. It came to dismissal. I found, when the moment arrived, that I had quietly revised the memory of what I had seen into something usefully uncertain, and I shook the young man's hand as he left, and wished him well, and meant it.`;
const MD1 = `Whenever Priya returned to the town she had grown up in, she was surprised to find it smaller, as though the years away had quietly let the air out of it. The main street she had thought grand was a single row of shops; the hill she had toiled up as a child she now climbed without noticing. She understood that the town had not shrunk, that it was she who had grown and gone and seen larger streets and steeper hills. And yet the disappointment was real, and it was not the town she missed but the child for whom the town had once been the whole of the world.`;
const MD2 = `The gardener plants the slow-grown oak
he knows he will not sit beneath,
and tends the sapling stroke by stroke
as one might tend a thing bequeathed.

He will not see the shade it throws
nor hear the noon birds in its crown;
he digs because the planter knows
the debt of every shade sat down.`;
const MD3 = `A study notes that towns with more bookshops have higher average lifespans and wonders aloud whether reading lengthens life. Before we shelve our medicines for novels, we might ask what sort of town can support a bookshop at all: one with disposable income, leisure, education and good clinics. Each of these bears on how long its residents live. The bookshop may be less the cause of the long life than a symptom of the same prosperity that buys the long life by other means.`;
const MD4 = `The old man fed the gulls each morning from the end of the pier, and the town had its opinions. Some said he was lonely; some said he was a nuisance, drawing vermin with wings; the children simply liked him. He said nothing to any of them. He had buried a wife who had loved the birds, and feeding them was neither loneliness nor nuisance but a conversation he was not ready to end, conducted in the only language still open to him.`;
const MD5 = `The pundit predicts a downturn within the next few years. If it comes, he is vindicated; if it does not, the few years have not yet elapsed. A forecast that no possible run of events could disconfirm tells us nothing about the world, though it may tell us a good deal about the forecaster, who has arranged to be right whatever happens. The test of a prediction is not whether it can come true but whether it could have come false.`;
const MD6 = `They paved the meadow for the cars
and named the road Meadow View,
as if a word set into tar
could keep a promise grass once knew.

The sign is honest, in its way:
it tells you what is not there now,
and every evening, come what may,
the traffic crawls where cattle used to bow.`;

